 By slicing the shape into smaller and smaller approximating rectangles
 and adding up the areas of those rectangles, the area can be approximated
 more and more accurately.
 The limit of these areas as the widths of the approximating rectangles
 aproaches zero is the area of the overlap.
 If you've taken calculus, that probably reminds you of integration, and
 it should! If you have not taken calculus, that probably sounds rather
 confusing and complicated, and it should! That is really the point.
 It is not an easy matter to calculate area, even of shapes that are easy
 to draw.
