The area of a bounded region of the plane, a shape 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, can be defined as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a polygonal region containing 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{R}$
\end_inset

 be a primitive partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (a finite set of parallelograms and triangles whose interiors do not overlap
 and whose union is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

).
 Define the norm of a partition, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $||\mathcal{P}_{R}||$
\end_inset

, as the maximum of the areas of the primitives in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{area}(S)=\lim_{||\mathcal{P}_{R}||\to0}\sum_{\substack{p\in\mathcal{P}_{R}\\
p\subseteq S
}
}\text{area}(p)
\]

\end_inset

whenever such limit exists.
