\begin_layout Subsection*
Areas and determinants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, if 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}^{m}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T(S)=\{T(s):s\in S\}$
\end_inset

.
 The image of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the set of images of all the points in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 To understand how the linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v})=A\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 affects areas, it is convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a product of elementary matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=E_{p}\cdots E_{2}E_{1}$
\end_inset

, as we have done before, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
TODO: reference back to where this has been done.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(S)=(T_{E_{p}}\circ\cdots\circ T_{E_{2}}\circ T_{E_{1}})(S)$
\end_inset

, if we can understand how linear transformations associated with elementary
 matrices affect area, we have a chance of understanding how general linear
 transformations affect area.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a row swap matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

 is a reflection about the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

, so in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a row replace matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

 is a shear transformation, and it is a known result of calculus that shear
 transformations do not affect area, so again 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a row scale matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

 scales shapes either horizontally or vertically—not both!—by a factor of
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=|s|\cdot\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 In every case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=|\det E|\cdot\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 Remember, the determinant of a row swap matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, the determinant of a row replace matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and the determinant of a row scale matrix with sacle factor 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{area}\left(T_{A}(S)\right) & =\text{area}\left((T_{E_{p}}\circ\cdots\circ T_{E_{2}}\circ T_{E_{1}})(S)\right)\\
 & =\text{area}\left(T_{E_{p}}\left(\cdots\left(T_{E_{2}}\left(T_{E_{1}}(S)\right)\right)\cdots\right)\right)\\
 & =|\det E_{p}|\cdots|\det E_{2}|\cdot|\det E_{1}|\cdot\text{area}(S)\\
 & =|\det A|\cdot\text{area}(S).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is noninvertible, then one of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of the other, so any linear combination of the columns is
 also a multiple of that column.
 Therefore, the image of any vector, which is a linear combination of the
 columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, is a multiple of that column.
 Thus the image of every vector lies on the line determined by that column,
 giving the image of any shape area zero.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\det A|=0$
\end_inset

, so again we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{A}(S))=|\det A|\cdot\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

